=== Education ===
In December 2021, the [[Girls' Day School Trust]], the largest network of girls' private schools in the UK, issued a blanket ban on trans girls being admitted to any of its schools.<ref>{{cite web |date=3 January 2022 |title=Leading group of private schools introduces 'unwise' ban on trans girls |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2022/01/03/trans-girls-day-school-trust-gdst/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220125182753/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2022/01/03/trans-girls-day-school-trust-gdst/ |archive-date=25 January 2022 |access-date=17 January 2022 |website=PinkNews}}</ref>

In August 2022, Attorney General [[Suella Braverman]] opined that it is lawful for schools to [[misgender]], [[deadname]], ban from some sports, reject from enrollment based on their trans status, and refuse any and all other forms of gender affirmation to trans kids, and that to recognise their identities as trans could qualify as "indoctrinating children".<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Wakefield |first1=Lily |date=12 August 2022 |title=Suella Braverman 'misinterpreted' equality law in 'ideological' attack on trans kids, barrister says |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2022/08/12/suella-bravermantrans-schools-speech-misinterpreted/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220812182351/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2022/08/12/suella-bravermantrans-schools-speech-misinterpreted/ |archive-date=12 August 2022 |access-date=12 August 2022}}</ref>

=== Sports ===
In September 2021, the UK Sports Council Equality Group issued new guidance saying that in their view, trans inclusion and "competitive fairness" cannot coexist in sports. The SCEG based its guidance on 300 interviews regarding personal opinions on the matter, conducted across 54 sports and 175 organisations, with only 20 of those interviewed being trans people.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Powys Maurice |first1=Emma |date=October 2021 |title=Glaring holes emerge in new UK trans sports guidance as athletes fear for their future |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2021/10/01/trans-sport-guidance-uk-backlash/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730144941/https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2021/10/01/trans-sport-guidance-uk-backlash/ |archive-date=30 July 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022}}</ref> In June 2022, the then UK Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport [[Nadine Dorries]] met with the heads of UK sporting bodies and told them that "elite and competitive women's sport must be reserved for people born of the female sex".<ref name="bbc.com">{{Cite web |date=29 July 2022 |title=RFL and RFU ban transgender women from competing in female-only forms of their games |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/62349297.amp |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220730145011/https://www.bbc.com/sport/62349297.amp |archive-date=30 July 2022 |access-date=30 July 2022}}</ref>

Since then, trans women have been banned from competing in [[women's sports]] in a wide array of disciplines, ranging from cycling to fishing.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Billson |first=Chantelle |date=29 November 2023 |title=Trans women banned from England Ladies team angling |url=https://www.thepinknews.com/2023/11/29/trans-women-banned-angling-ladies-team/ |access-date=11 November 2024 |website=PinkNews {{!}} Latest lesbian, gay, bi and trans news {{!}} LGBTQ+ news |language=en-US |archive-date=30 September 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240930175302/https://www.thepinknews.com/2023/11/29/trans-women-banned-angling-ladies-team/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=British cycling federation bars transgender women from competing in female category |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/cycling/british-federation-announces-tighter-rules-around-trans-non-binary-athletes-2023-05-26/ |work=Reuters}}</ref>

== International responses ==
In 2021 the [[Council of Europe]]'s Committee on Equality and Non-Discrimination warned that:
<blockquote>
ongoing social, political and legal debate [in the United Kingdom (UK)] about what
constitutes harmful discourse when it comes to trans people and their rights, and
arguments defending freedom of expression have been – and are still being – used
as a tool to justify transphobic rhetoric, further penalising and harming already
marginalised trans people and communities
</blockquote>
and concluded the {{" '}}gender-critical' movement, which wrongly portrays trans rights as posing a particular threat to cisgender women and girls, has played a significant role in this process".<ref name="Walters">{{Cite journal |last=Walters |first=Mark Austin |year=2024 |title=Legalizing transphobia: from courtroom to legislature, how gender-critical activism is hurting us all |journal=Journal of Law and Society |language=en |volume=51 |issue=3 |pages=343–366 |doi=10.1111/jols.12491 |issn=0263-323X|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=27 September 2021 |title=Combating rising hate against LGBTI people in Europe |url=https://assembly.coe.int/LifeRay/EGA/Pdf/TextesProvisoires/2021/20210921-RisingHateLGBTI-EN.pdf |website=Council of Europe Committee on Equality and Non-Discrimination |access-date=31 October 2024 |archive-date=23 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210923211038/https://assembly.coe.int/LifeRay/EGA/Pdf/TextesProvisoires/2021/20210921-RisingHateLGBTI-EN.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

In May 2023, a [[United Nations]] investigation found that the British [[Equality and Human Rights Commission]] (EHRC) had deliberately acted with the objective of reducing [[human-rights]] protections for transgender people who had legal gender recognition.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=UK: Keep calm and respect diversity, says UN expert |date=11 May 2023 |publisher=United Nations |url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2023/05/1136567}}</ref>

